      <hedline>
        <hl1>Politics and Cancer</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Joseph D Policano letter, commenting on Oct 25 article, deplores Pres Clinton's decision to sign without ceremony bill providing treatment to breast cancer patients in order to circumvent inviting Rep Rick Lazio, bill's original sponsor and Hillary Rodham Clinton's opponent in New York State Senate race</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Under Circumstances, No Pomp as Clinton Signs a Bill'' (news article, Oct. 25):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Under Circumstances, No Pomp as Clinton Signs a Bill'' (news article, Oct. 25):</p>
        <p>You report that President Clinton signed a bill to provide treatment to breast cancer patients without a signing ceremony, in part because it would have been awkward to invite  Representative Rick A. Lazio, the  sponsor of the original House measure, who is Hillary Rodham Clinton's opponent in the New York Senate race. While such behavior is normal for politics, the hypocrisy is staggering.</p>
        <p>Shouldn't cancer patients be outside the boundaries of such a cheap political act? This is another shameful reflection on Bill and Hillary Clinton and makes one wonder just how deep their empathy for cancer patients runs.</p>
        <p>JOSEPH D. POLICANO  East Hampton, N.Y., Oct. 25, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
